{
  "texts": [
    "In our work, we used the open-source library Langchain for this purpose [11], and suggest that the interested reader begin with Langchain's documentation to understand the depth of the problem.",
    "The goal of this portion of the RAG system is to break large documents into smaller chunks, typically by number of words or number of sentences, for later processing.RAG systems operate by mapping sentences into a high-dimensional vector space, which is a process known as \"embedding\" the text.",
    "Embedding models are neural networks that have been trained to maintain semantic similarity between sentences by mapping semantically similar sentences to vectors that are close in the Euclidean distance sense in the vector space [12].",
    "It is this \"semantics-as-distance\" mapping that makes RAG so powerful for providing ground truth to an LLMwe can pass a query into the RAG system, extract the embedding of the query, and find the semantically closest document vectors to that query.",
    "Logically, the semantically closest document vectors should contain information relevant to the query for the LLM to use to generate its response."
  ]
}